{"candidates":[{"content":"{\"claim\":\"The simultaneous collapse was a contingent conjuncture of heterogeneous local crises lacking unified causal structure, while Egyptian persistence reflects its distinctive socio-political ecology\",\"mechanism\":\"No single mechanism; instead, independent local stressors (drought severity, palace factionalization, raiding intensity) combined stochastically. Egyptian survival was not a controlled variable outcome but a result of its geographically peripheral, ecologically buffered position within the same interactive system.\",\"scope\":{\"covers\":[\"Mycenaean Greece\",\"Hittite Anatolia\",\"Ugarit\",\"Levantine city-states\",\"Egyptian persistence\"],\"excludes\":[\"Minoan decline (earlier)\",\"Mesopotamian stability\",\"Iron Age recovery patterns\"]},\"forbidden\":[{\"case\":\"Demonstrable correlation between collapse timing and a single shared variable (e.g., identical tephra layer, synchronized warfare horizon) across all four regions\",\"eval\":\"rubric:std-hist\"},{\"case\":\"Evidence that Egyptian elite consciously adopted collapse-avoiding reforms in anticipation of shared threats\",\"eval\":\"rubric:std-hist\"},{\"case\":\"Archaeological demonstration that any two collapsed regions shared identical failure sequences at identical chronometric resolution\",\"eval\":\"rubric:std-hist\"}],\"prose_notes\":\"The 'Systems Collapse' model (A2) overdetermines causality by retrofitting network theory onto patchy evidence. The archaeological record shows desynchronization: Ugarit burns c. 1190, Hattusa c. 1180, Mycenaean centers c. 1200-1150. This temporal spread exceeds what single-cause mechanisms predict.\"}","typicality":0.35,"neighbours":["A3","A8"]},{"content":"{\"claim\":\"Climate-driven agricultural failure triggered palace system collapse through the specific mechanism of centrally-administered redistributive economies that could not adapt to resource variance\",\"mechanism\":\"Palace economies operated as command redistributive systems with fixed surplus extraction quotas. When the 4.2ka-like Late Bronze Age drought regime reduced carrying capacity, palaces could not downscale extraction without delegitimizing ruler-god theology or triggering elite defection. This structural brittleness caused cascading administrative failure, while Egypt's dispersed irrigation and private grain entrepreneurship provided adaptive slack.\",\"scope\":{\"covers\":[\"Hittite Anatolia\",\"Mycenaean Greece\",\"Ugarit\",\"Levantine city-states\"],\"excludes\":[\"Egyptian full prosperity (survived 'diminished')\",\"Mesopotamian irrigation regimes\",\"Early Bronze Age analogues\"]},\"forbidden\":[{\"case\":\"Evidence that Mycenaean wanax-administered economies included significant private land tenure and market-like grain storage independent of palace control\",\"eval\":\"rubric:std-hist\"},{\"case\":\"Paleoclimate reconstructions showing no significant precipitation anomaly c. 1200-1150 in Anatolian or Aegean catchments\",\"eval\":\"rubric:std-hist\"},{\"case\":\"Archaeological demonstration that palace collapse preceded rather than followed agricultural stress markers (storage abandonment, crop transition)\",\"eval\":\"rubric:std-hist\"}],\"prose_notes\":\"Explicitly synthesizes A2's systemic interdependence claim with A4's structural buffer claim, while denying A3's contingency thesis. The mechanism is institutional: not drought simpliciter, but drought + redistributive extraction rigidity.\"}","typicality":0.55,"neighbours":["A2","A4","A8"]},{"content":"{\"claim\":\"The collapse constituted an ontological security crisis when performative ruler-god theology encountered irreconcilable experiential disconfirmation, causing elite defection and administrative demobilization\",\"mechanism\":\"Palace civilizations depended on cyclical ritual performance guaranteeing cosmic and agricultural order. Prolonged drought, earthquake, and military failure after c. 1250 constituted cumulative 'ontological disconfirmation'—evidence that king-god mediation failed. Elite withdrew ritual and administrative labor (not merely military service), causing 'demobilization' more than destruction. Egypt's theology located divine efficacy in afterworld maintenance and Ma'at-cosmic order, not direct agricultural performance, permitting ideological absorption of stress.\",\"scope\":{\"covers\":[\"Hittite royal ritual (iskalli, AN.TAH.SUM festivals)\",\"Mycenaean wanax ideology (Linear B 'potnia' theology)\",\"Ugaritic Ba'al cycle kingship\",\"Levantine temple-palace integration\"],\"excludes\":[\"Mesopotamian royal ideology (different theological structure)\",\"Iron Age prophetic movements\",\"Egyptian full military success\"]},\"forbidden\":[{\"case\":\"Continued elite administrative production (sealings, scribal archives, building dedications) at major centers after onset of stressors without reduction in quality/quantity\",\"eval\":\"rubric:std-hist\"},{\"case\":\"Evidence that Egyptian New Kingdom royal theology underwent collapse-analogous crisis (e.g., Amarna suppression was structurally similar) and recovered without institutional change\",\"eval\":\"rubric:std-hist\"},{\"case\":\"Archaeological demonstration that administrative abandonment postdated physical destruction layers (fire, weapon trauma) at multiple palace sites\",\"eval\":\"rubric:std-hist\"}],\"prose_notes\":\"Develops A7's legitimation-crisis thesis with specific institutional mechanism: elite withdrawal of performative labor. Directly challenges A5's invasion-dominant and A6's earthquake-dominant accounts by reversing destruction-abandonment causal order. Highly atypical in privileging ideological causation over materialist baselines in Bronze Age historiography.\"}","typicality":0.15,"neighbours":["A7","A3","A8"]}]}